\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Monday}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 - Plenty of livestock to move but just normal fighting all day to get licences.  We always get there before the day is out but it is getting frustrating that it takes you all day to get there.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Tuesday}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  - I left the yard at 07.00 with a wagon.  Going to Pe
rth for a load of sheep.  It's nice to get away from the phones and get peace and see the countryside.  It's nice to go into Scotland and see things looking normal.  Rather than going South and seeing the scars in the fields where piers have been.  A cons
tant reminder of a short time ago.
\par I was talking to the Trading Standards officer while I was loading.  She told me the rules in Scotland were changing "more rules to get used to".  You just get used to one set of rules then they change.  A lot of the time for the worse.
\par When I got back to the office mayhem.  I had organised a load of sheep to come from Belgium to Cumbria. Officials in Dover were not happy because they had not received the paperwork from Belgium.  When the animals have been vet}{\fs24\insrsid5066474 t}{
\fs24\insrsid13964281 ed in Belgium the vet has to stamp the papers and fax them to Dover so they can issue a licence for the livestock to travel in Britain.  The vehicle was sailing a
t 21.00.  It made the boat with 10 minutes to spare after a lot of phone calls and persuasion.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Wednesday}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  - The lads arrived back from Belgium mid morning.  All the fuss had been in Dover.  The DEFRA official in Dover told them he didn't really know what w
as required.  If he doesn't know how are we meant to know.  After all it's them making the rules.
\par When we washed the vehicle out there had to be a MLC (?) official and a vet to pass it clean. The vet had forgotten his official stamp so he put his thumbprint on the form and signed it.  What chance have you got.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Thursday}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  - Delivered sheep to 2 farms at Waterbeck and Canobie.  Nice to see happy faces.  Would have talked all  day but about the weather and DEFRA.  When I presented the licences to the farmers I 
was surprised in a way they didn't know what they had to do with them.  There are so many different areas nobody is sure they are right or wrong.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Friday}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  - Organising a load of cattle out of Belgium for next week.  I phoned Belgium and Dover for some guida
nce.  For once I got somebody with sense in Dover.  He faxed me an authorisation number for the licence so the driver could fax everything himself from Belgium.  Done everything I can now hope everything will be ok this next week.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Saturday}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  - Had a headache - }{\fs24\insrsid9574325 laid}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  about all day.  Felt better in the afternoon - England beat Scotland at Rugby.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Sunday}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  - The Boss went away for the afternoon so I was on duty for 3 or 4 hours.  One driver phoned - stopped at Penrith by the police - wouldn't let him go any furth
er because of the wind.  The forecast was for the wind to be down later.  A few phone calls were made and another driver found so both could leave early on Monday morning and go down and back, because the licence run out Monday p.m.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s4\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel3\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs28\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 2
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Everything org
anised, hopefully the wagon set for Belgium, fingers crossed. Restocking a farm in Cumbria tomorrow, no licences so I phoned DEFRA. The livestock was coming from four different farms four different vehicles from all over the country. When I got hold of th
e right person at DEFRA he had faxed the licences to the wrong Vets. He faxed them to the right Vets so we could set the vehicles off.
\par 
\par Tuesday
\par All the licences arrived in the right place so the farmer at Hutton roof is very pleased. He is excited about get
ting animals back on his farm after so long. Leading up to a movement the farmers get cross and frustrated with all the officialdom but when everything eventually falls into place it seems to add to the excitement, either that or it is just relief at last
 they can get on with their normal working lives. 
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par A good friend of mine was getting his first cows home today. In the morning he was up to high do panicking did he have the right licences, was the transport in place and running on time. By night
 he was over the moon, cows home, everything ok. He said it was great to hear cows beckoning in the buildings again.
\par The wagon arrived from Belgium ok and the farmer was very happy with his cattle. 
\par 
\par Thursday
\par }\pard\plain \s16\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f1\fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs24\insrsid13964281 The other side of the coin today, a load of ped
igree pigs to go to Italy next month. The regulations that I have say all imports must come through Dover but they don\rquote 
t say anything about exports. First I phoned Dover to find out, after speaking to four people in Dover I was passed to someone who gave me the number for Page Street in London. I phoned page street, the dreaded DEFRA headquarters. I couldn\rquote 
t believe the lack of knowledge of the rules. After 8 different people all saying \'93not my department sorry\'94 I was given the number of an animal health office in Lincoln where I was hoping to ship out of. }{\f0\fs24\insrsid9574325 
When I phoned Lincoln surprise, surprise the girl who deals with exports was out for lunch. }{\f0\fs24\insrsid13964281 When I got hold of her after lunch she wasn\rquote t 100% sure so she asked state vet in the office who phoned London to 
make sure. It was ok to export out of other ports but why couldn\rquote t London tell me that?
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid7888855 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Friday
\par Fax machine is red hot today. A whole new set of rules coming out for spring. Reading the new regulations, it should make life a lot easier. Some rules are good but some are silly, just what was expected. It seems to me these people making these rules don
\rquote t trust anybody and think they have no common sense. Maybe if they tried talking to people who have to use these rules, life could be easier for everybody. They might even get a bit of respect.
\par 
\par Saturday
\par I\rquote ve got my son this weekend. Me and a few friends went kart racing, we were practising for going to Manchester in two weeks time, we are in the finals of the }{\fs24\insrsid16677158 Marie Curie}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  karting challenge. It\rquote 
s great to get on the track, forget everything and have fun.
\par 
\par Sunday
\par Wet day again, sat at home and built a model car with my son. Mam and Dad came to see us. Talked about all sorts apart from Foot and Mouth. Then I took }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [son]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 to Abington to meet his Mam and go home. Quite enjoyed the weekend.
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s4\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel3\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs28\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 3
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Monday
\par I went to Lanark today for a load of sheep. I thought things would be easier today. Loading the sheep was but all the restrictions as far as paperwork is concerned are still in place in Scotland but not in England.
\par When I got back from Lanark I made some enquiries about the new rules; things are easier but still very restricted.
\par 
\par Tuesday
\par I got a phone call from one of the girls I work with at Penrith. It was great to hear from her and find out what everybody had been up to in the last six months. The sting in the tail of the phone call was DEFRA were still trying t
o sort a claim out from the Cull last April. I had to go and hunt paperwork out they needed. I find it hard to believe claims are still being sorted out-I also find it hard to believe a farmer could sit back for 10 months and then ask for payment for his 
livestock. It makes you sit and think how long this will go on for?
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par Things are fairly quiet today, everything going well for a change. Spent most of the day phoning different ferry companies for prices and reviews because of the time that has lapsed since we used them regularly.
\par 
\par Thursday
\par A lot of livestock moving today. Some for slaughter, some from restocking, some just extra stock on farms, some from England to Scotland and vice versa. You need a license for some and not for others. Spent a lot
 of time on the phone to local officers of the areas the livestock was coming from. Things weren\rquote t too bad everybody I spoke to could give me an answer straight away.
\par 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Friday
\par I have another wagon in Belgium today it went away yesterday and drove right to 
the first farm in Belgium. The two drivers need al their tome to reach the farm accurately for delivery; it is the first load to come into Scotland because of the travelling times allowed. I got a phone call at 13.00; the driver in Belgium has a problem w
ith paperwork but didn\rquote t do anything about it, so the wagon didn\rquote t get on the ferry. The regular people in Dover were off today and the ones that were there didn\rquote t know what they had to do, so they didn\rquote 
t phone authorisation through in time. I phoned my cus
tomer in Carluke he gave me a number for a man in Seerad headquarters in Edinburgh. I phoned the man in Edinburgh and explained what had happened. He said to me to leave it with him and he would get back to me in the next ten minutes. Five minutes later t
h
e phone rang, I was surprised it was the man in Edinburgh, he told me the head welfare officer from DEFRA in London would phone me. I had hardly put the phone down when the man from London phoned, I was frustrated and angry so he got it full pelt. Once I 
h
ad got it off my chest and calmed down a bit he got the chance to speak. After all this time I was actually speaking to somebody that understood and knew what you were talking about. I spoke to him for about half an hour. He was sympathetic with a lot of 
problems we had and promised to look into them. He also assured me the people in Dover would be disciplined and learned the proceeding properly so it wouldn\rquote t happen again. \'93We will wait and see\'94
\par 
\par Saturday
\par 3.30 am the phone rang, the drivers were back from Belgium. I had arranged for them to ring when they got home because they wouldn\rquote t get the ferry they were meant to they didn\rquote 
t have time to deliver the sheep. As we had used all our own drivers on the Frid
ay I had to go and deliver the sheep. When I got to Carluke the farmer was pleased 1. Because he eventually got his sheep and 2. Because they had travelled well. He said that despite all the hassle of the last month it was a relief the sheep were home. I 
am full of cold but feel quite good after seeing and hearing the farmer.
\par When I got home 10.30 I went to Andrew, my friend who has a farm. I went to collect his sheep that I fetched from Iscay in January. This was the last of his livestock home. That was hi
m fully restocked. It was nice to walk round the farm and see livestock in the sheds. He had some cows and calves. The calves suckling their mothers and shipping round the shed was so good to see especially when only six months ago there was nothing but e
mptiness. The farm seemed alive again.
\par 
\par Sunday
\par Didn\rquote t get up till late, feel crap, full of cold. Laid about and played games with my son. As the day went on I felt a bit better. Say thinking \'93wonder what next will bring\'94. As usual the weekends don\rquote t seem to last very long.  
\par }\pard\plain \s4\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel3\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs28\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid10180473 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 4
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 
First live sale at Carlisle today. My boss went to Carlisle so I was left in the office on my own. Things are very busy so it was hectic. My friend from the farm, his sister came for supper tonight. It was good to see a happy smiling face. 
\par I had a wagon went to Italy today with pedigree breeding pigs. My shooting on Friday must have done some good. The wagon got out of Dover no problem.
\par 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 
\par 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Tuesday
\par I went and picked my new glasses up today, I can see small print a lot better, lets hope it cures some of the headaches I\rquote ve been having lately. We are getting to know more about the new rules, things are not much better than they were.
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par Trying to get to grips with these new rules. It\rquote s a bit of a nightmare really. Everybody is confused at what you can do and what you can\rquote t do. The rules seem so stupid.
\par We are trying to organise to fetch sheep to Longtown for the first live sale tomorrow, but it is difficult. We have sheep coming from Perth but the timing is difficult. The market won\rquote t be open until 6.00 that\rquote 
s if it passes an inspection, but at the same time the livestock has to be in before 8.00. Hope the wagon doesn\rquote t break down or get a puncture or we are in trouble.
\par 
\par Thursday
\par First live sale in Longtown today. It was nice t
o hear the echo around the yard of the auctioneer. 18 months ago I never really noticed it but today the sound was a lot more distinct. Every time I walked out of the office it was the first thing I heard. Some of the rules seem to be very stupid everybod
y knows foot and mouth is a airborne virus, but despite this before anybody could enter the office or the canteen they had to wash their hands. Also a wagon driver or a driver couldn\rquote 
t wash their hands in the same basin as a farmer. Once their hands were washed they could go to the office, handle the same paper, talk to the same person, then go and have their dinner together in the canteen! 
\par 
\par Friday
\par Things are not so busy today so I was on a wagon for a while. I went to Hexham to load cattle. There were thre
e men on the gates in and out of the market. I had to fill a form in before I could get in the market. About cleansing and disinfecting the wagon. The only thing was he never asked yet where the wagon was getting cleansed. When I got in to the market ther
e was one man and he didn\rquote t care who\rquote 
s cattle I got as long as the market was empty. There was no paper work with the cattle so therefore very little traceability. It is so frustrating you try and do everything right and sensible but the ones that make the rules don\rquote t seem to care.

\par 
\par Saturday
\par Brian, a good friend of mine called in to see me today. We sat and talked about things that had happened while foot and mouth was in its height. Brian worked on the \'85\'85\'85 cull on the Scotch side while I was working this side of the border.
\par We were comparing stories in a way and laughing at things that normally you wouldn\rquote t laugh at, but as the saying goes if you didn\rquote t laugh you would cry.
\par 
\par Sunday
\par Went to Manchester for the }{\fs24\insrsid16677158 Marie Curie}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 Karting final. Five of us went to Manchester, it was a great place and a great racing circuit but the karts were rubbish. Despite that we had a great day and a good laugh. I wasn\rquote 
t very well coming home I think it must have been the fumes. I had a headache and bad stomach, as soon as I got home I went to bed.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s4\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel3\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs28\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 5
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Still don\rquote 
t feel well today, full of cold, bad head and sore stomach but as usual off to work. Can\rquote t really be bothered today but I have a wagon going to Germany with pigs. Everything went without a hitch.
\par 
\par Tuesday
\par Busy at work today, more and more farmers phoning wanting livestock fetched from various parts of the country, things seem to be looking better.
\par I watched a programme on TV about the year of Foot and Mouth. I watched as all the thoughts of nearly a year ago came flooding back. Seeing people I knew and their livestock on piers fetched a tear to my eye.
\par After that on the news two sheep found with legions in their mouths. All you can think is not again. 
\par After watching that programme then seeing the news and thinking of all the horrific things that happened and to think it could be happening again doesn\rquote 
t bear thinking about. Just when you think things are getting better you kicked in the teeth again.
\par A lot of people accused people of making a lot of money out of foot and mouth at the time. Yes, a lot of people did make money but for the work that they had done they needed paying for it.
\par I sat at home thinking tonight yes I made money but I wouldn\rquote t go through it again not even if they paid me ten times as much. It\rquote s not the money it\rquote s the animals-the people-the livelihoods-the life. Put all that together you can
\rquote t put a price on the way of life. All the money just helped people to try and build that way of life. To think this disease might be coming back is bound to put everybody in the livestock industry in turmoil. Fingers crossed it\rquote 
s a false alarm.
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par Everybody breaths a big sigh of relief the first blood tests have come back negative. There seems to be light at the end of the tunnel again.
\par I sent a wagon to Hexham today for a load of sheep. There were four lots in Hexham Mart and three on farms all supposed to be DERFA approved and when the wagon got to Hexham and out the sheep on there trading standards would not let him go to
 the farms. If he had gone to the farms first and then to Hexham there would have been no problem. I had to send another wagon to the farms. So the job took two wagons instead of one. I can\rquote 
t see what difference it makes when the sheep are going to kill they can\rquote t spread any diseases when they are dead.
\par 
\par Thursday
\par Still al clear, no news is good news. The sale at Longtown ran a lot smoother today and sheep were a good trade. Things are starting to look better. 
\par I went to Siloth to pick up a load of fertiliser. It was a very busy place it means spring is in the air and everybody is looking forward instead of standing still.
\par 
\par Friday
\par Short day at work today, finished early 6pm going to the road haulage association annual livestock dinner dance (the annual cow punchers ball). Seen a lot of faces I hadn\rquote 
t seen for a long time, conversation was good and everyone was in good humour.
\par The chairman of the R.H.A made a speech in which he said there was big changes coming up from \'85\'85. He said they were trying to stop livestock transport altogether, looks like we will have a battle on our hands. What people don\rquote 
t realise is without livestock transport breeding programmes will stop. Some breeds of livestock will disappear. Some rare breeds sheep, cattle, pigs all types travel
 all over the country as part of bug breeding programmes to increase numbers of certain breeds.
\par 
\par Saturday
\par Quiet day today, feeling under the weather a little. It must have been a better night than I thought Laid about most of the day and watched the rugby.
\par I felt better as the day went on good job going for tea tonight. }{\fs24\insrsid11086707 D}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 , my boss and Ian a friend from Stirling and our partners went for a bar meal to a country pub owned by }{\fs24\insrsid11086707 D}{
\fs24\insrsid13964281 \rquote s uncle.
\par The pub was fairly quiet when we went in but by the time we had our meal the pub was very busy. There was a lot of local farmers that were out for a meal as well. It was good to see people having confidence to go out again and enjoy themselves.
\par 
\par Sunday
\par Had a lie in this morning, didn\rquote t get up until nearly lunch time. Went shopping then went to visit my Dad, it is his birthday today. Spent the afternoon with my parents, came home and relaxed.
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s4\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel3\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs28\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 6
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Looks like it\rquote s going to be a busy week, the order books full. There\rquote 
s a lot of sheep moving. This week because they are fetching a good price. There is also a lot of dairy cattle to come to Cumbria this week.
\par 
\par Tuesday
\par I think everybody in Cumbria wants to restock their farms this week. The phone just doesn\rquote t stop. The funny thing is Cumbria and Devon were the hardest hit areas despi
te that there is livestock coming from Devon to Cumbria and Vice versa. This to me proves the point about breeding livestock, different breeds and bloodlines you can\rquote t buy the bloodlines in a fifty mile radius. Most mule breeding stock and }{
\fs24\insrsid10180473 S}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 waledale sheep the best bloodlines are bred in Cumbria. So when you farm in Buckingham or Norfolk for example, how can you breed good sheep if you are not allowed to transport them. That\rquote 
s what I was meaning in a previous diary about stopping livestock transport. 
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par Went to Siloth for a load of fertiliser today, it was pouring down. When I got loaded I had to put sheets on the load. I stood there soaking and cold thinking all the hassle in the office is not so bad after all. Got back to the office and the boss wa
s a bit under pressure things very busy so it was back in at the deep end. We spent the next few hours sorting tomorrow\rquote s work and were both out on wagons leading stock into Longtown. 
\par 
\par Thursday
\par 06.00 start this morning off my first load of sheep for Longt
own. When I arrived at Longtown there were 3 DEFRA officials on the gate and one mart staff. The mart worker gave me a form to fill in as to where I was going to cleanse the vehicle. The 3 DEFRA officials were making sure the wheels were disinfected, the 
o
nly thing was it was an automatic wheel wash. When I got to the loading banks there was another three officials and as far as I could see none of them seemed to know what they were meant to be doing. After I was empty I had to go to the wash and have my w
heels washed before I could leave the market. When the wheels had been washed I drove out of the market through the automatic wheel wash? Yet I was allowed to go back to my depot without washing out! What\rquote s the point?
\par If it wasn\rquote t for the auction staff aski
ng whose livestock I was carrying nobody would know. All those officials all over the market but nobody asked me where or whose livestock I had on, I would have thought that might just be important. I could have fetched livestock from anywhere, where is t
here so called tractability.
\par Later on in the afternoon I went back to load a load of sheep. I drove straight into the market, nobody on the gate. There was one MLC official on the loading banks. He never asked whose livestock I was lifting or where it was going. I just can\rquote 
t understand where all the sense in this is apart from jobs for the boys.
\par 
\par Friday
\par Went out for a meal tonight with all the staff from Penrith that I worked with on the contiguous cull-it was good to see them all again after 8 months and catch up on what\rquote 
s been happening. Everybody was in good humour and we had a good laugh. It was so different, everybody was relaxed instead of been tense and sort of aprehensive-2 of the girls are pregnant which shoes there is a future to come out of foot and mouth.

\par 
\par Saturday
\par Set off to go to a sale of surplus equipment that Snowie}{\cs20\fs24\super\insrsid10180473 \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s21\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10180473 
\fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\cs20\super\insrsid10180473 \chftn }{\insrsid10180473  Haulage contractor used to transport culled livestock to burial sites
\par 
\par }}}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  used in dealing with foot and mouth. I cued in traffic for about half an hour then gave up and turned round and came home.
\par 
\par Sunday
\par The weather is crap today so I just relaxed at home with my wife and son.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 7}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
\par Monday
\par  Things look as if they could be a
 bit quieter this week. Despite as the day goes on more farmers are ringing wanting cattle fetched up from the South. Its now about 6 months since the last case of foot and mouth and we are still restocking and will be for a long time. It shows just how m
any animals and farms were taken out due to foot and mouth. It also makes you realise just how much devastation there was in Cumbria.
\par 
\par Tuesday
\par WE had a visit from DEFRA today they want us to help them compile a database of livestock haulers. It seems funny to me that the people who set the standards. We have to follow and make the rules, we have to abide by don\rquote 
t know who has to abide by them. This is all to do with trace ability no wonder things were such a mess. 
\par We had a phone call yesterday from someone 
in DEFRA asking about trace ability. The girl wanted to know how we kept a trace on our movements. We told her everything we moved was in a computer and on delivery notes and by livestock movement sheets. The girl then asked what a livestock movement shee
t
 was and could we fax one to her so she could see what they looked like. Between DEFRA not knowing who is carrying livestock and not knowing now or what records are kept. Its easy to see why the foot and mouth crisis was such a mess. Its amazing a year on
 they are finally consulting people that count, its such a pity they didn\rquote t think of doing that a year ago things might have been a lot different. But I suppose that\rquote s something we will never know.
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par Things are getting busier as the week goes on; n
early all of the abattoirs are looking for sheep the demand is getting better. The public confidence in eating meat again is growing also the export of meat is quietly growing again. The price of live animals is quite good which makes things look good. Th
ere is starting to get a bit of atmosphere in the farming community again which is a good sign of things getting better.
\par 
\par Thursday 
\par I took a load of sheep into Longtown this morning, there were more officials than last week, I\rquote ve never seen so many in one place. I don\rquote 
t know whether it was right or not but one of the auction staff told me one of the auctioneers had fell out with the head vet. The upshot of them falling out was more officials to make sure everything was done the way they wanted. In my mind th
ey went too far some farmers and buyers fell out with them as well basically because they went too far. At the end of the day we are all here to work together and common sense will always prevail so why upset people and push them to the limit when there i
s no need.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par Friday
\par We are preparing the work for the weekend because my boss is going away for the weekend and as usual when he is away it looks as if it is going to be busy.
\par One of our drivers phoned in this afternoon he had a load of fertiliser on for local farm but when he phoned the farm to say he was coming the farmer told him he wouldn\rquote 
t be there to lift it off. The farmer told him if he left the tractor out he could lift it off himself so he phoned to see if someone could go and help him. I went to 
the farm with the driver to drive the tractor for him. While I was lifting the fertilizer I was thinking 12 months ago we wouldn\rquote 
t be allowed near the farm let alone in the farm driving his tractor, it shows how things can change so much in a short space of time.
\par 
\par Saturday
\par  Went into work at 9.00, supposedly for one hour just to sort out men and wagons for Sunday and Monday. I gave up at 18.30 and still had some of Mondays work still to sort out. There is 4 wagons going int
o Scotland in the morning they are picking sheep up off 18 different farms from Forfar to Gretna. I don\rquote 
t think DEFRA realise that at this time of year when fat lambs are getting less but demand is still there the distance that has to covered to make up numbers to keep up with demand.
\par 
\par Sunday
\par The phone started ringing at 03.30 one of the wagons going to load wouldn\rquote t start so I got up and went and helped put another wagon ready to get him away. Went back to bed at 03.45. The phone rang again at 08.15 one of
 the drivers had got to his first farm to find nobody there, no sheep and no way he could get in with the size of vehicle he had. I got up and went to work and phoned the auctioneer who had bought the sheep so he went and sorted it out.  I went back home 
a
nd had some breakfast. About 12.30 the first wagon phoned it loaded and the others all phoned within half an hour. I went to work and phoned drivers who were going with wagons to come in. I printed their delivery notes. Once the wagons were in and gone ag
ain I went home. 
\par Another drivers\rquote  wife phoned at 22.30 she had taken her husband to hospital with pains so he wouldn\rquote t be at work in the morning. Looks like another early start in the morning.
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s4\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel3\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs28\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 8
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Went to Lanark today when I got there I discovered so
me of the sheep I was supposed to get had already gone with the wagons yesterday. I was there at 09.30 but had to wait until 12.30 because they were going to buy sheep in the live sale to fill the wagon.
\par I seen a lot of faces that I hadn\rquote t seen for over a 
year there was a lot of handshaking and catching up. It was good to see everybody again. The one thing I noticed with not seeing people for so long how much people had changed i.e. aged and put weight on. 
\par 
\par Tuesday
\par We had a visit from an auditor he wanted 
to see all our accounts for work done for DEFRA. He is looking through everything because he has to make sure there was no wastage because the money to pay for foot and mouth is coming from Europe. He was asking why there was so many people and vehicles w
orking and why after the job was done did it take so long to do the paperwork and finish off. It didn\rquote t take a lot of explaining, \'93DEFRA\'94.
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par Quiet day today spent most of the day catching up on paperwork and filing. We were trying to catch up on so
me of the men who worked for us when we were doing the cull for DEFA. I ratched out some of my books with lists of people who were employed or who had their names forward for employment. Looking at the books there was a big list of names. It was surprisin
g how many people offered to help not just because of the money but because they wanted to help. In the height of the cull we had approx 200 people employed and about 98% of them were local people.
\par Thursday
\par DEFRA phoned today asking for the same information I sent them a few weeks ago, it seems to me they either don\rquote 
t care and just leave things lying around and it gets lost or they think people are trying to hide something from them. Nobody has anything to gain from hiding anything from them so it must be they don\rquote t care.
\par 
\par Friday
\par The boss is away for the weekend today so I\rquote m left with everything again. I am trying to get all the weekends work done today as it is my Fathers retirement party tonight. He is actually 66 but because a lot of family and friends are
 connected to farming we had to postpone it last year . The party starts at 19.30 I was hoping to be there on time to see his face as he knew nothing about it. But I didn\rquote 
t get finished until 20.00. Everybody was already there when I got there and I missed the first half an hour I was there because my phone wouldn\rquote 
t stop ringing. When the phone stopped ringing and I went back I enjoyed what was left of the night. I saw a lot of Aunties and Uncles I hadn\rquote t seen for a long time because of foot and mouth then 
being busy after foot and mouth. We had a good laugh and some good conversations. It was all the better because F&M was never mentioned everybody was in good spirit. A lot of the time I am a bit apprehensive about going out because people keep asking me w
hat was it like, what did you see, I just get a bit sick of talking about it all the time.
\par 
\par Saturday
\par Spent nearly all day phoning farmers all over Scotland to arrange to pick their sheep up tomorrow as I didn\rquote t get it all done yesterday. Spent quite a while
 trying to get drivers for the wagons as well a lot of our part time drivers are farmers or farmers sons so with them restocking and weather being good they are all at home. Six or eight months ago it wasn\rquote 
t a problem because none of these men had anything at home to work with. Most of these men wanted to work then basically to make a wage and to get them out of the house away from bad memories. 
\par 
\par Sunday
\par Had a lie in this morning the phone didn\rquote t ring until 09.30 it was great.  Only in work for about 4 hour
s so I got some time to relax and spend time with my wife and son. The only thing was after I took my son home I had to go back into work for a couple of hours and sort out Mondays work. I finally got home about 9pm never mind one more week at work then I
\rquote m off for a week. 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s4\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel3\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs28\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 9
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Busy day today, plenty of cattle moving about there is a lot of cows to move this week.

\par 
\par Tuesday
\par Everything seems to be going well for the amount of livestock being moved. Now that people are getting used to the regulations there isn\rquote 
t as many hiccups. DEFRA are even issuing licences when people apply for them. Its about time they got their act together.
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par Out in a wagon today I went to Ancroft, Codingham, Cockburnspath, Duns, Greenlaw and Hawick to collect sheep. All the sheep I collected were what they call self-declaration which means the farmer fills a form in. On the form they have to put
 their name and address, their holding number and the number of sheep and where they were going. On the form there is a Collum the driver has to fill in the name of a hauler and registration number.
\par This is supposed to be DEFRA\rquote s way of tracing the animals back to origin. The farmer doesn\rquote 
t have to put ear numbers on the form so they could put any sheep on the wagon and the driver would know no differently. So to me all the hassle of forms and different pick up points is a waste of time, there is no trace ability.
\par 
\par Thursday
\par  In the office today, a live sale in Longtown.  Longtown was quiet today not a lot of livestock in today. We found out that last week there was an argument with the head vet and some of the buyers. The auctioneers had found out that there
 was going to be an invasion of head DEFRA officials on Longtown so they got most of their customers and buyers to take their sheep to Dumfries on Wednesday. They were right, there was more officials than people and livestock put together. What are they t
r
ying to prove or are they just being awkward to keep themselves in a job. Why do they pick on Longtown could it be that it was the first market to be confirmed and was at the centre of foot and mouth or could it be it was one of the biggest and most succe
ssful in Europe they want to make it a Scapegoat to convince Europe of something.
\par 
\par Friday
\par 
\par My son came to stay last night for Easter after today I am on holiday for a week so I want as much done today as possible. I have my tippers to catch up with and get the paperwork for them up to date. 
\par I have a load of deer going to Lithuania in the middle of April so I was trying to organise a lot of this before I go away for the week.
\par Everything I could do was done. I am going to Kilmarnock tonight my Mother in law is coming to see her parents before lambing time so I am taking my wife to see them all. It\rquote s quite good because this time last year we couldn\rquote 
t have done this.
\par 
\par Saturday
\par 
\par At Kilmarnock the start of a week off I have been looking forward to this for a while. Me and son went for a look round the car shops and the sports shops, }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [son]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 wanted a Man united top for Easter but we couldn\rquote t get one to fit him so I\rquote ve promised to get him one at Carlisle if they have them. }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 \rquote s Mam and sister came about tea time th
is afternoon so we had a good night catching up on the last few months. 
\par 
\par Sunday
\par 
\par Didn\rquote t do a lot today, went for a walk into the town and got some bits and pieces for the garden. }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [son]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  didn\rquote t want to come with us he stayed in the house stuffing himself with Easter eggs.

\par 
\par 
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s5\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel4\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Dairy 10
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 
Went for a walk into town again today just to get out of the house when the weather is quite good. When we came back I was in the garden with }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 \rquote 
s Grandfather, he is a keen gardener. I got some plants off him for my own garden so it looks like I will have to do something with it. We had our tea then came home it\rquote s great I don\rquote 
t have to get up in the morning a week at home with my son.
\par 
\par Tuesday
\par 
\par Got up this morning and cleaned up in the yard and put the rubbish in the van. When }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [son]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 got up I got him to get dressed while I made breakfast. After breakfast we took the rubbish to Carlisle to the tip. My Dad was there with some Rubbish as well so that was a good excuse to go for a coffee.
\par I borrowed my Dads pressure wash I decided to wash my yard and house at home. Dads pressure washer wasn\rquote t very good so I phoned my brother and got his. I had to wait until he got home from work so I dug the garden over. 
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par 
\par Started to wash the yard today I got all the yard and the back of the house washed, it was good being outside in good weather. With the garden tidied up and the yard looking clean and tidy it looks a lot better. I never had time to do it last 
year because I was working 7 days a week for months so I got nothing done at home. 
\par 
\par Thursday
\par 
\par I washed all the front of the house this morning, it looks a lot better as well. I went into Carlisle this afternoon for one or two bits and pieces for putting up a trellis on the wall for plants to climb.
\par While I was at Carlisle I bumped into }{\fs24\insrsid484382 o}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 ne of the girls I worked with at Penrith when the cull scheme was on. We hadn\rquote t been able to get hold of }{\fs24\insrsid484382 [her]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 when we had our night out. So we had a good blether and caught up we exchanged numbers so we could get hold of each other when the next night out was.
\par 
\par Friday
\par 
\par Got a phone call this morning, my friend asking me if I wanted to go to a farm sale with him so I said I might as well when I had the chance.
\par I went to Carlisle with }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [son]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 and opened a bank account for him and set up a standing order for him from my account so that he has something for the future whatever that might hold. I only hope things are better than they are now.
\par We went to the sale with another farmer who has had enough and getting out while he can. Prices were good so there must be some optimism in the farming community.
\par 
\par Saturday
\par 
\par My cousin came this morning he had asked me to get him some Ewe lambs so we went to have a look at some that I had found. He liked the look of them and bought them.
\par }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [son]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  went away with Mam and Dad for a week up in Caithness. Me and }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  went to Carlisle to look at wallpaper for the bedrooms. (oh what fun!)
\par 
\par Sunday
\par 
\par Quiet day today the weather is good so me and }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  spent the day outside putting the plants in the garden. I also made a tub for growing strawberries. The garden is starting to look good now.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s5\qj \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel4\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 11
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid13964281 Back to work today, nothing\rquote s been done while I\rquote 
ve been away. I have a lot of work to catch up with. I tried to book the ferr}{\fs24\insrsid10180473 ie}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 s for the deer going to Lithuania. I wish I was still on holiday everything that could go wrong is going wrong. The p
ort I was planning to sail out of Denmark isn\rquote 
t allowed to sail livestock because they have no vet. I spent nearly all day trying to reorganise everything so that I can sail out of Copenhagen but everything needs to be put back a day. Back in the deep end 
hassle last week was so good, no phones, no grief just do jobs at my own leisure with no hassle. But I suppose somebody\rquote s got to do it.
\par 
\par Tuesday
\par 
\par I got the boats booked but now I can\rquote t contact a vet in Copenhagen. I need the vet at free port but I couldn\rquote t get my answer. One good thing DEFRA have passed the route plan so all I need is the vet.
\par 
\par Wednesday
\par 
\par I have a load of pigs going to Italy next week as well so I am trying to organise that as well. Italy isn\rquote t so bad as there is just one ferry crossing. Th
e only thing I have to do is work out the route plan and send it to DEFRA and see if they pass it.
\par 
\par Thursday
\par 
\par I was leading sheep into Longtown this morning. If you are not washing the vehicles out at the market you have to fill out: where the vehicle is k
ept, reg number, type of vehicle and the drivers name and address. I filled the form out as Mickey Mouse, Disney World, Florida handed it in and drove out of the market. How are they going to trace that vehicle? It just proves the system they have in plac
e is a waste of time and the people implementing it don'\rquote  know what they are doing.
\par I still can\rquote t get hold of a vet in Copenhagen I phoned two people who we have taken pigs to Lithuania before but they couldn\rquote t help me much either. I am starting to panic a little now because if he gets to Copenhagen and can\rquote 
t get a vet the captain of the ship might not let him sail.
\par 
\par Friday
\par 
\par The route plan for Italy has been passed all I need to do is get some Euros for the road Tolls in Italy. The pig company phoned me today they want a load of pigs taken to Greece a week on Monday. I tried to book Ferr}{\fs24\insrsid10180473 ie}{
\fs24\insrsid13964281 s right away but at first I ran into a brick wall. Normally the wagons go via Bari to Patras but since September the 11}{\fs24\super\insrsid13964281 th}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  German and Italian tourists are driving to Greece o
n holiday rather than flying. I have left it with the travel company we use sometimes to try and get me a ferry. I phoned DEFRA at page street in London to see if they could help me contact a vet in Copenhagen. They had no contact numbers and the ministry
 vet couldn\rquote 
t help me much. What he did tell me that because the deer will vetted and blood tested before they go on the wagon he will already have stamped papers. He faxed me a letter for the driver to take with him to say that DEFRA had approved the movem
ent of deer and a direct contact number for him. So somebody from Copenhagen could phone him if they had any doubt. Not that he could do much in England when the wagon would be in Copenhagen, but at least he was trying to help.
\par 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid484382 
\par 
\par 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Saturday
\par 
\par Didn\rquote t do a lot today we had a house full this morning so it was dinner time before I got anything done. }{\fs24\insrsid484382 [friends]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  were in what a team my sides were sore with laughing.
\par 
\par Sunday
\par 
\par Went for a run round the garden centres today to see what plants were going to put in this year.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par  }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 12
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Mon
\par The 2 wagons going abroad se off this morning, one going to Italy with pigs and the other to Lithuania.  The pigs isn't a problem everything is in place for them.  The deer are still a problem, I still can't get hold of a vet
 in Copenhagen to let them know the deer would be there Tuesday night for Wednesday morning and they would need to be vetted.  But they weren't very helpful either. I don't know what more I can do apart from cross my fingers.
\par Still trying to get a ferry from Italy to Greece. I think I might have a crossing from Bari to Brindisi, it's not what I wanted as it means a 12-14 hour journey across Greece. I will have to work out a route plan for the journey now.
\par 
\par }\pard\plain \s16\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f1\fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs24\insrsid13964281 Tuesday Cotswold phoned today and told me things ha
d changed for the Greece load as in some of the pigs were coming from Aberdeen.  The means the pigs will need an extra rest stop in France so the journey from there on to Greece will now need to be put back a day.  I phoned the travel Agent right away to 
r
ebook the ferry and hoped he could do it.  I then phoned Cotswold and complained.  How do they expect somebody to organise a job when they only have half the details. I told them how difficult it was to get a ferry and if I couldn't get a new booking the 
pigs wouldn't be able to go and it wouldn't be my fault.
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\fs24\insrsid484382 D}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 is in Copenhagen but we will have to wait until morning as there was nobody at the port in Copenhagen when he got there.
\par 
\par Weds
\par }{\fs24\insrsid484382 D}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  went to get his ferry this morning. When he went into the office for his ticket he told the team he needed a vet. The man took him to the door and pointed to a door across the road way. }{
\fs24\insrsid484382 D}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  went across, knocked on the door and the vet came.  The vet asked him if his deer were all right and if he checked them.  }{\fs24\insrsid484382 D}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  told him he's
 been feeding them regularly for the last two days and that he had just fed them again and they were fine.  The vet stamped his papers and went. He didn't even look at the animals.  All that hassle for nothing, I needn't have bothered.
\par I managed to change 
the ferry for Greece so drew up a route plan and sent it to Cotswold for them to get it approved by DEFRA.  Just before I finished tonight I got a phone call from Cotswold saying DEFRA had rejected the route plan, they say the vehicle could go another 3 h
ours before needing to stop for the rest period.
\par 
\par Thursday I made a new route plan for Italy with a stop 3 hours further into Italy than before and faxed it to Cotswold. By tea-time it was back rejected again. DEFRA saying it was now too far.
\par I asked }{\fs24\insrsid484382 G}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  about it and asked him what I could do. }{\fs24\insrsid484382 G}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 is one of the bosses and he used to do all the continental work but he runs a depot in Carlisle now so the continental work was passed to me.  I told him I didn't want to do it as it wasn't worth the hassle. I also tol
d him I didn't know enough about the continent to do it and it was taking up too much of my time so other jobs were getting neglected . He told me I would have to do it as there was nobody else so I told him and the rest of them if I had to carry on doing
 the continent, once this Greece load was done I would resign.  There was no reply, whether they thought I was just saying that in the heat of the moment I don't think they thought I was serious.
\par 
\par Fri
\par I sent Cotswold another route plan with a destination between the two points I had previously put forward and faxed it to them to put to DEFRA. Low and behold it came back again.  DEFRA say it is too far again so I done another and sent it to them  T}{
