\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 13
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Mon
\par The wagon is away to load and set off for Greece, something is bound to go wrong.  It did go wrong when they got to Lincoln, they were held up for 5 hours,  I just hope they ha
ve enough time to get to Bari because if they miss that ferry we're all in shit street.
\par 
\par Tuesday 
\par Spent all day catching up on work I had missed last week with trying to organise this load for Greece.  BY night I was just about there, another half day should get me caught up.
\par 
\par Weds
\par I got caught up this morning so I was delivering fertiliser this afternoon for a couple of hours. It was great to be out of the office for a while. No hassle, a bit of crack with the farmers. It was good driving round the country
side seeing the lambs in the fields skipping about and the odd field of cattle.  It looks so much better than it did this time last year, clear skies, life in the fields instead of dead animals and black smoke everywhere.
\par 
\par Thursday }{\fs24\insrsid484382 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Of}{\fs24\insrsid484382 f}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  work today.  I went to Kennacraig near Campeltown and caught the ferry to Islay.  I arrived in Islay  about 3 o'clock and travelled down to }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{
\fs24\insrsid13964281 's Mam and Dad. The lambing is going pretty well. They only have about 35 left to lamb out of 150. It's so nice here, no noise, n
o hassle, just totally different.  No cars going past your window every two minutes, no telephones ringing all the time.  All you can hear is the wind and the sea.
\par 
\par Fri
\par I went with A}{\fs24\insrsid484382  }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 today delivering eggs and potatoes to the different villages round Islay.
 I seen a few people I hadn't seen for a while and caught up on gossip of what has been happening.  It's funny even a year on people are still asking what it was like living in Longtown and all the F&M roundabout me.  They want to know because they only s
een it on TV but you get a bit sick of talking about it all the time.
\par }{\fs24\insrsid484382 
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Sat
\par I helped A}{\fs24\insrsid484382  }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 this morning feeding lambs and moving some of the ones that had lambed into different fields. We sorted the barn door and then I fixed his pick up for him.  This afternoo
n I helped him with a fence at the house.  We put a mesh on it like a screen to stop some of the wind getting into the garden. The wind over here can be savage and with it coming off the sea it turns the plants in the garden black with the salt.  I went f
o
r a walk with the rifle this afternoon. Their neighbour is overrun with rabbits so she asked if I would go over a shoot a few. I got 4 but best of all was the peace.  Out on the shore on my own, it was so peaceful.  All you could hear was the sea and the 
gulls.  I was late back for my tea, I just lost track of time being there in the peace and quiet, nobody to bother me and no hassle, it was great.
\par 
\par Sun
\par No electric this morning so we couldn't have breakfast until 13.00.  We had breakfast, then me and }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  went to the nursing home to visit her Gran. }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
 is a bit upset today because we are going home tomorrow. Her heart is still on the island.  I don't really want to go either. I would love to live over here away from the hustle and bustle where tomorrow is another day.  You never know, one day.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Diary 14
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Mon
\par Came home from Islay today. }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  is a bit upset, she misses country life. The livestock and the freedom.  The think she misses most is looking out of the window either over the Atlantic or out over 
the fields.  She says all you see out of our windows is other people's houses.  She also misses the animals just being able to walk out of the door and they are there.
\par 
\par Tuesday Back to reality today with a bang.  The wagon that went to Greece has had probl
ems. When travelling with livestock you are allowed to travel 24 hours then yu have to stop for 24 hours and rest the animals. In that 24 hours you are supposed to unload the animals, rest them load them again and continue your journey.  There is a provis
i
on in them rules which says with pedigree livestock, as long as there is adequate food and water on the vehicle and the animals have room to lie down, the 24 hour rest period can be spent on the vehicle.  The latter being written in the WATO (Welfare of A
nimals Transport order) in Britain but not in the European version of the WATO rules.
\par 
\par The drivers had stopped at a Truck stop about 4 hours off Bari in Italy, they had fed and watered the pigs, bedded them down and filled the water tanks and were taking th
eir 24 hour rest.  They had been there about 6 hours when they were knocked up out of their beds by an Italian vet and the police.  The vet told them that they were breaking the law, he said they should be at a proper staging post with lairage facilities.
 
 They showed him the route which DEFRA had passed and they also showed him the health and pedigree certificates for the pigs.  They explained that the pigs were hybrids and full pedigree so it wasn't really safe to take them off where there was other anim
a
ls and also explained about the 24 hours been taken on the vehicle because the pigs had adequate food and water and were all lying quite peaceful.  The Italian vet still wasn't happy, he was reading the WATO rules by the letter. Consequently he took them 
to an abattoir that had been closed for 3-4 years, made them take the pigs off for 245 hours and fined them 3000 Euros.
\par 
\par When you are in a foreign country you don't stand much chance. They don't seem to care about the health of animals as much as we do.  Th
e abattoir they took them to used to kill horses - Sadam Insane - and was left in the state it was the day sanctions were fetched in.  All we can do is hope the pigs haven't picked up a disease.
\par 
\par Weds
\par I've got to the state where I am losing interest in my 
job and the livestock haulage industry. When you used to go into a market there was a buzz about the place but now there isn't half as many people go to markets so there isn't the same atmosphere.  Also when you went to the market, you had a good crack, a
 
good laugh with lads from other haulage firms but now everyone is sick with rules and regulations.  Also when you were loading in a market, everybody used to muck in and help each other but now everybody is working against the clock and they just get on, 
look after themselves and go.  The fun has gone out of the job.
\par 
\par Thursday
\par Early start again this morning. I was leading sheep into Longtown for the sale today.  The market was quite busy this morning, there was a lot of stock in.  Things seem to be getting 
back to something like normality apart from all the yellow jackets still walking about.
\par I was moving cattle out to grass today which is a good sign of summer coming. It is god to see the animals back out in the fields.  AS the restocking is still ongoing it is starting to show by the number of fields that have livestock in them.
\par 
\par Fri
\par Boss away for the week-end again he is away on a golf week-end.  Things are fairly quiet and not just as busy so hopefully I will have a quiet week-end.  The phone rang at 11.3
0 pm, it was my boss. Fishers cattle had burst a wall and got out on the road and could I go and help get them back in. That's a good start to a quiet week-end.
\par 
\par Sat
\par There was a sale of pedigree livestock at Carlisle today, there was about 200 bulls for sa
le.  I had one wagon there just in case any of our customers were there.  One or two had phoned to say that they were going to the sale but it would depend on the price of the animals.  The customers our lad went to see decided by lunchtime that things we
r
e too expensive to buy and he went home.  Just an hour after he left the phone rang, it was somebody looking for transport for 1 bull to Aberdeen, then half an hour after that it was somebody looking for transport for 1 bull to South Wales.  The rules are
 
you have to register to buy in the market and also tell the market who is  doing your haulage because the livestock has to be out of the market by 10pm the same night.  You would think people knowing what the rules are would have arranged their transport.
 Also the market if they had checked their forms to see if they had made arrangements and if not they could suggest somebody instead of waiting till they had bought livestock.
\par 
\par It makes it hard work for everybody especially the markets because if the livest
ock isn't moved the market can't have a sale next day. This has happened on a few occasions at Carlisle lately. You would think they would have learned and started to check for things like that.
\par 
\par Sun
\par The phones are quiet today and there is only one wagon out today so I have time to spend with }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  and }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [son]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
.  The weather is quite good today so we went for a run, the only problem is we can't go too far because I'm on duty is anything goes wrong I need to go to work. I can't be too far away.
\par I only need to go into work for 10 minutes tonight to put 1 DLY note out once I get the final numbers of the load.
\par 
