\par  SEPTEMBER
\par Week 33
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Things are getting really busy, there is a lot of breeding sales coming up next week or two and some of the silly rules and regulations are not going to help at all.  Now that all sheep have to be licensed again you lose so 
much time collecting licences before the wagon can set of.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Tuesday
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 I went to Castle Douglas, Dumfries and Lockerbie today.  What a difference, no licences I can go to all three markets, then go and deliver the sheep, no hassle ass long as I don't cross th
e Border.  It's absolutely crazy, you can go 50 yards into Scotland and do whatever you like until you come back to England.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Wednesday
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 A fairly big day at Longtown today - ewe lambs, gimmers and store sheep.  It's surprising just how much livestock is in 
the county again and good quality breeding stock.  It took me 1 hour to get the licenses I needed for the stock I was taking out today as far as I can see it's just a farce and everybody I have spoke to is of the same opinion.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Thursday
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 
Longtown fat sale today - this is what they call designated slaughter day that means everything that is sold must be out of the market by 10 pm and must be killed within 72 hours.  On top of all that you still need a license to move anything.  I can't see
 why you have to have a license when it's going to be killed and if they say for traceability what about all the stock that was moved between May and September?  "Jobs for the boys"?
\par 
