\par After a good day with no hassle I was back to reality and bloody DEFRA rules again today.  I am trying to organise a load of cattle from Denmark to Balymoney in Ireland but because of regulations, I don\rquote t know how I\rquote 
m going to do it.  Because of the travelling time between the two countries, the journey time is too long.  You are allowed 14 hours, I hour\rquote 
s rest, then another 14 hours.  Then the livestock has to be taken off and rested for  24 hours before it can continue its journey.  If a time runs out whi
le on a ferry it only has to be rested for 12 hours.  Because these are in calf heifers, it would be better for them to do the whole journey in one go but it will still be difficult to organise.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\insrsid13964281 Thursday
\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 I got a phone call today from an auctioneer in Irel
and.  He had got a load of cattle for one of his customers near Bristol.  The cattle travelled up 3 week ago but when they arrived at Larne the Irish Authorities found a mistake on the paperwork and put the wagon straight back on the boat.  The cattle hav
e been on a farm at Stranraer for two week and he was wanting to know if we could take them back to Bristol for him.  The cattle can\rquote t move for another week because DEFRA put a 21 day movement order on them and they can\rquote 
t go to Ireland.  They have to go back to the farm of origin which is the farm they came off, go through all the tests again, then stay there for 30 days after the tests, before they can be exported again.  With all that the man in Ireland doesn\rquote 
t want the cattle now.  I can\rquote t see why they couldn\rquote t sort the paperwork  out at Stranraer and let the cattle go to Ireland. , instead of trailing them all over the country for 2 month, where\rquote s the animal welfare?
