\par }{\fs24\insrsid13964281 Back in the grind again. Two year ago I studied to become a vocational assessor in livestock transport but with F&M it all got put on the shelf.  I had qualified as an assessor before F&M but I didn\rquote 
t get my NVQ in road transport. So in the New Year the rules are changing and drivers of livestock vehicles will have to have a certificate so I am going to carry on and get my NVQ.
\par 
\par Tuesday
\par I didn\rquote t start very early today.  I took }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  to the hospital for her second scan.  It was amazing to see the baby.  Everything was ok \endash 
 two legs, two arms.  The midwife is happy with everything so }{\fs24\insrsid4859116 [wife]}{\fs24\insrsid13964281  doesn\rquote t need to go back, she just has to keep seeing her own midwife.
\par Things are staring to get busier at work with Christmas sales and the lead up to Christmas.  It is the Christmas store sale at Stirling so I am going up there tomorrow.
\par 
\par Weds
\par I went to Stirling this morning.  I saw a big change in the market but I seen a lot of faces I hadn\rquote t seen for a long time \endash  I enjoyed the change.  I had a good yarn to a lot of people I hadn\rquote t seen in a long time.  They couldn
\rquote t believe how strict the rules were with us in England.  In Scotland the only thing they can\rquote t do is buy stock in one market then take them to another to sell them again.  Because of the 21 day rule, they have to either tak
e them home for 21 days or send them direct to an abattoir.  I\rquote ve never seen an MLC official all day.  I loaded 7 wagons but I didn\rquote t need to get 1 licence. In Scotland all movements are recorded by computer.
\par 
